SIMPLE: interweave
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: interweave
<hw>in`ter*weave"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& obs. p. p.</pos> <conjf>interwove</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p.
p.</pos> <conjf>interwoven</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>interweaving</conjf>.]</vmorph>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To weave together; to intermix or unite in texture
or construction; to intertwine; <as>as, threads of silk and cotton
<ex>interwoven</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Under the hospitable covert nigh⟦br⟧
Of trees thick <qex>interwoven</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To intermingle; to unite intimately; to connect
closely; <as>as, to <ex>interweave</ex> truth with falsehood</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Words <qex>interwove</qex> with sighs found out their way.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>interwish</ent>⟦br⟧
